urls.title: A novel mutation in EROS (CYBC1) causes Chronic Granulomatous Disease
urls.description: Chronic Granulomatous Disease (CGD) is a severe inborn error of immunity characterised by opportunistic infection with catalase positive organisms and sterile granulomatous inflammation. CGD is caused by a failure of reactive oxygen species (ROS) production by the phagocyte NADPH oxidase, a multi-protein subunit enzyme comprising membrane bound subunits and cytosolic regulatory subunits. Mutations in the genes encoding the subunits of the phagocyte NADPH oxidase causes CGD. gp91phox, which facilitates electron transfer from NADPH to molecular oxygen, is the most common subunit to be mutated across cases of CGD. Previously, we and others have described a novel form of CGD (CGD5) secondary to lack of EROS (CYBC1), a highly selective chaperone for gp91phox. EROS deficient cells express very low levels of gp91phox and its binding partner p22phox, but EROS also controls the expression of other proteins such as P2X7.
